<section id="sec-title-slide"><h1 class="title">Mortality</h1><h3 class="author">ECON 499: Economics of Inequality</h3><h3 class="date">Winter 2018</h3>
</section>

<section>
<section id="slide-orgd7a0cfa">
<h2 id="orgd7a0cfa">What are the consequences of inequality?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Philosophical debates on inequality are hard to resolve</li>
<li>Can instead focus on outcomes</li>
<li>Does inequality make people worse off in an objective way?</li>

</ul>

</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org774ecb6">
<h2 id="org774ecb6">Chetty et al (2016)</h2>
<ul>
<li><i>The Association Between Income and Life Expectancy
in the United States, 2001-2014</i></li>

</ul>

</section>
</section>
<section>
<section id="slide-org9669814">
<h2 id="org9669814">Life expectancy</h2>
<ul>
<li>Calculate the mortality rates for the cross section of every age</li>
<li>Use the mortality rates to calculate life expectancy at any given age</li>
<li>Alternatively, calculate the percentage of people who survive to a given age</li>
<li>Compare that to the distribution of income at each age</li>

</ul>

</section>
</section>
